Building emx, GCC, GDB, utilities, and libraries
================================================

The makefiles have been created for dmake 3.8.  Use the initialization
file /emx/etc/dmake.ini for dmake.

IMPORTANT: Set the following environment variables (insert the correct
drive letters) unless indicated otherwise:

  set emxopt=-t                     Truncate file names to 8.3
  set emx=c:\emx\emx.exe            Speed up locating emx.exe for MS-DOS
  path c:\emx\bin;%path%            Search c:\emx\bin for programs
  set switchar=-                    dmake should use / instead of \

To speed up compiling the libraries, you might want to set the
following environment variables under OS/2:

  set gccopt=-pipe                  Use pipes instead of temporary files
  set gccload=5                     Keep executables in memory for 5 minutes

You can use either the patched GNU sources or you can apply the
patches to the sources yourself, see the batch files in the
subdirectories of /emx/gnu/patches.  These batch files need Larry
Wall's patch utility (aka GNU patch nowadays).  It should be named
lwpatch.exe to avoid conflicts with OS/2's patch.exe program.  Some of
the batch files require the `sed' program and other tools.  The batch
files have been tested on an HPFS filesystem only.  The batch files
must be run in the \emx\gnu directory:

  cd \emx\gnu
  patches\gcc\inst

The makebin batch file converts a.out files to .exe files, using
appropriate options.  The .exe files are put into the directory
/emx/new.

After testing, you can move the .exe files from /emx/new to /emx/bin.


Preliminary tasks
-----------------

Create the directory /emx/new:

  md \emx\new


Building emx
------------

You need MASM 6.00A (the `A' is important).

  cd \emx\src\dos
  dmake
  cd \emx\src\os2
  dmake


Building emxomf, emxomfar, emxomfld and listomf
-----------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\src\emxomf
  dmake


Building emxbind
----------------

  cd \emx\src\emxbind
  nmake


Building emxcat
---------------

  cd \emx\src\emxcat
  nmake


Building emxdoc
---------------

  cd \emx\src\emxdoc
  dmake


Building emxexp
---------------

  cd \emx\src\emxexp
  dmake


Building emximp
---------------

  cd \emx\src\emximp
  dmake


Building emxload
----------------

  cd \emx\src\emxload
  dmake


Building emxstack
-----------------

  cd \emx\src\emxstack
  dmake


Building touch and updt
-----------------------

  cd \emx\src\utils
  dmake


Formatting the documentation (.doc and .inf files)
--------------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\src\doc
  dmake


Building the FPU emulator
-------------------------

  cd \emx\gnu\fpu-emu
  dmake
  makebin emxfpemu


Building GCC
------------

Edit makeexe.cmd and dostage1.cmd to contain the correct path for
gcc.exe, cpp.exe, cc1.exe, as.exe, ld.exe and emxl.exe.

  cd \emx\gnu\gcc-2.8
  dostage1
  makeexe
  movstage stage1
  dostage2
  makeexe
  movstage stage2
  dostage3

The files common to . and stage2 must be identical.  Now build the EXE
files in \emx\new:

  makebin all-gcc

To recompile GCC without going through two or three stages, use
compile.cmd.


Building the new GNU binary utilities (ar, size, nm, objdump) and gprof
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\gnu\binutils.26
  cd bfd
  dmake
  cd ..\libibert
  dmake
  cd ..\binutils
  dmake
  cd ..\gprof
  dmake
  makebin new-binutils


Building GAS
------------

  cd \emx\gnu\binutils.26
  cd libibert
  dmake
  cd ..\gas
  dmake
  makebin all-as


Building GDB
------------

You need sed for compiling GDB.  GNU Bison is required for compiling
DUEL.  You can omit DUEL by editing \emx\gnu\gdb-4.16\gdb\makefile:
remove the references to duelgdb.o and ../../duel/duel.a.

  cd \emx\gnu\gdb-4.16\readline
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\gdb-4.16\bfd
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\gdb-4.16\libibert
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\duel
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\gdb-4.16\gdb
  dmake
  makebin gdb


Building the texinfo utilities (info, makeinfo, texindex)
---------------------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\gnu\libtxi
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\info
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\makeinfo
  dmake
  cd \emx\gnu\texindex
  dmake
  makebin all-texinfo


Building the old GNU binary utilities (ld, strip)
-------------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\gnu\binutils.old
  dmake
  makebin old-binutils


Building genclass
-----------------

  cd \emx\gnu\libg++-2.8.1.1a\libg++\genclass
  dmake
  copy genclass.exe \emx\bin


Building GCOV
-------------

Type the following commands to build gcov.exe:

  cd \emx\gnu\gcc-2.8
  gcc -O  -I. -Iconfig -Zsmall-conv -o \emx\bin\gcov.exe gcov.c


Building GPPDEMID
-----------------

MS C 6.00A is required for building gppdemid.dll.

  cd \emx\gnu\gppdemid
  dmake
  copy gppdemid.dll \emx\dll


Building the libraries
======================

Don't forget to set the environment variables as indicated above.


Building the emx libraries
--------------------------

Note that the `make' command in directory \emx\src\lib is a batch file
invoking dmake!  You should not invoke dmake directly.

Before building the emx libraries, some subdirectories must be
created:

  cd \emx\src\lib
  make mkdir

See \emx\src\lib\makefile for the available targets.  For instance, to
build /emx/lib/st/c.a, type:

  cd \emx\src\lib
  make c-st

When building sys.lib, note that you need MASM 6.0 to build thunk.obj.
If you don't have MASM 6.0, you should avoid deleting thunk.obj.

The `sed' tool is required for building emxlibc*.dll, c_import.a, and
c_import.lib.

If the DLLs are currently in use while they are built, copying to
/emx/dll fails and you'll find the DLLs in /emx/src/lib/cdll.

To build all the emx libraries and C library DLLs, type:

  cd \emx\src\lib
  make all-os2

To build all the libraries and object files, type

  cd \emx\src\lib
  make all-os2-bsd

Building /emx/lib/gcrt0.o requires installation of bsdsrc.zip.  To
build gcrt0.o, type:

  cd \emx\src\lib
  make o-crt-bsd

Building /emx/lib/gcc.a (and emxlibc*.dll) requires installation of
the GCC sources.  You may have to change the value of the GCCSRC macro
in \emx\src\lib\gcc\makefile.


Building termcap.a (the GNU termcap library)
--------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\gnu\termcap
  dmake
  copy termcap.a \emx\lib

This builds /emx/lib/termcap.a.


Building stdcpp.a (the GNU standard C++ library)
------------------------------------------------

For building stdcpp.a you need OS/2; the library sources must be
installed on an HPFS drive.  The -t option must not be set in the
EMXOPT environment variable.  If you haven't applied long.cmd in
\emx\include, you should run long.cmd now to rename the include files
to the original long names before building stdcpp.a:

  cd \emx\include
  long

The C++ include directory \emx\include\cpp is also required for some C
programs and therefore must be added to the end of the search path for
C headers:

  set c_include_path=%c_include_path%;c:/emx/include/cpp

(By default, the C compiler -- in contrast to the C++ compiler -- does
not search the C++ include directory.)

Type the following commands to build stdcpp.a:

  cd \emx\gnu\libstdc++-2.8.1.1\libio
  dmake iostream.list
  cd ..\libstdc++
  ar cr ..\libiberty\libiberty.a
  dmake
  copy "libstdc++.a" \emx\lib\stdcpp.a

If you get the error message

  SYS0010: The environment is incorrect.

unset some unused environment variables and try again.


Building gpp.a (the GNU C++ library)
------------------------------------

For building gpp.a you need OS/2.  The library sources must be
installed on an HPFS drive.  The -t option must not be set in the
EMXOPT environment variable.  If you haven't applied long.cmd in
\emx\include, you should run long.cmd now to rename the include files
to the original long names before building gpp.a:

  cd \emx\include
  long

The C++ include directory \emx\include\cpp is also required for some C
programs and therefore must be added to the end of the search path for
C headers:

  set c_include_path=%c_include_path%;c:/emx/include/cpp

(By default, the C compiler -- in contrast to the C++ compiler -- does
not search the C++ include directory.)

Type the following commands to build gpp.a:

  cd \emx\gnu\libg++-2.8.1.1a\libg++\src
  del libgpp.a *.o
  dmake
  copy libgpp.a \emx\lib\gpp.a

If you get the error message

  SYS0010: The environment is incorrect.

unset some unused environment variables and try again.


Building objc.a (runtime library for the Objective C language)
--------------------------------------------------------------

If you have applied long.cmd in \emx\include, you should run short.cmd
now to rename the include files to the short names (as distributed)
before building objc.a:

  cd \emx\include
  short

Then, type the following commands to build objc.a:

  cd \emx\gnu\gcc-2.8\objc
  dmake
  copy st\objc.a \emx\lib\st
  copy mt\objc.a \emx\lib\mt


Building check.a (runtime library for bounds checking)
------------------------------------------------------

Type the following commands to build check.a:

  cd \emx\gnu\gcc-2.8\bounds\lib
  make libcheck.a
  copy libcheck.a \emx\lib\st\check.a


Building regexp.a (regular expressions)
---------------------------------------

  cd \emx\src\regexp
  dmake
  copy regexp.a \emx\lib

This builds /emx/lib/regexp.a.


Building curses.a (the BSD curses library)
------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\bsd\curses
  dmake
  copy curses.a \emx\lib

This builds /emx/lib/curses.a.


Building btermcap.a (the BSD termcap library)
---------------------------------------------

  cd \emx\bsd\libterm
  dmake
  copy termcap.a \emx\lib\btermcap.a

This builds /emx/lib/btermcap.a.


Building bsd.a (partial BSD C library)
--------------------------------------

  cd \emx\bsd\libc
  dmake
  copy bsd.a \emx\lib

This builds /emx/lib/bsd.a.


Building db.a (the BSD database library)
----------------------------------------

For building db.a you need OS/2 2.x.  The library sources must be
installed on an HPFS drive.  (OK, I'm lazy.)

  cd \emx\bsd\db
  make                          (make.cmd invokes dmake via sub.cmd)
  copy db.a \emx\lib

This builds /emx/lib/db.a.

